If you do any DOM modifications, they can change your element&#39;s visibility of course.


**Guidelines and common pitfalls:**

**Maybe you need to track page zoom / mobile device pinch?** jQuery should handle [zoom/pinch][10] cross browser, otherwise [first][11] or [second][12] link should help you.

If you **modify DOM**, it can affect the element&#39;s visibility. You should take control over that and call `handler()` manually. Unfortunately, we don&#39;t have any cross browser `onrepaint` event. On the other hand that allows us to make optimizations and perform re-check only on DOM modifications that can change an element&#39;s visibility.

**Never Ever** use it inside jQuery [$(document).ready()][13] only, because [there is no warranty CSS has been applied][14] in this moment. Your code can work locally with your CSS on a hard drive, but once put on a remote server it will fail.

After `DOMContentLoaded` is fired, [styles are applied][15], but [the images are not loaded yet][16]. So, we should add `window.onload` event listener.

We can&#39;t catch zoom/pinch event yet.

The last resort could be the following code:

    /* TODO: this looks like a very bad code */
    setInterval(handler, 600);

You can use the awesome feature [pageVisibiliy][17] of the HTML5 API if you care if the tab with your web page is active and visible.

