```css
#parent {
   position: relative;
}
    
#child1 {
   position: absolute;
   top: 0;
}
  
#child2 {
   position: absolute;
   bottom: 0;
}
```

This works because `position: absolute` means something like &quot;use `top`, `right`, `bottom`, `left` to position yourself in relation to the nearest ancestor who has `position: absolute` or `position: relative`.&quot;

This is the same working principle for height or width, when you use a relative unit. The value is applied in relation to the [containing block.][1]

So we make `#parent` have `position: relative`, and the children have `position: absolute`, then use `top` and `bottom` to position the children.


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Containing_block

