&lt;h3&gt;Proper uses of IMG&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use &lt;code&gt;IMG&lt;/code&gt; if you intend to have 
people &lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/questions/492809/when-to-use-img-instead-of-css-background-image/492835#492835&quot;&gt;print your page&lt;/a&gt; and you want the image to be included by default. 
&amp;mdash;&lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/users/20153/jaytee&quot;&gt;JayTee&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use &lt;code&gt;IMG&lt;/code&gt; (with &lt;code&gt;alt&lt;/code&gt; text) when the image has an important semantic meaning, such as &lt;a href=&quot;http://24ways.org/2005/naughty-or-nice-css-background-images&quot;&gt;a warning icon&lt;/a&gt;. This ensures that the meaning of the image can be communicated in all user-agents, including screen readers.&lt;/li&gt;

&lt;/ol&gt;




&lt;h3&gt;Pragmatic uses of IMG&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;

&lt;li&gt;Use &lt;code&gt;IMG&lt;/code&gt; plus alt attribute if the image 
is &lt;a href=&quot;http://stackoverflow.com/questions/492809/when-to-use-img-instead-of-css-background-image/492834#492834&quot;&gt;part of the content&lt;/a&gt; such as a logo or diagram or person (real person, not stock photo people).
&amp;mdash;&lt;a href=&quot;http://stackoverflow.com/users/42147/sanchothefat&quot;&gt;sanchothefat&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use &lt;code&gt;IMG&lt;/code&gt; if you rely on browser scaling to render an image in proportion to text size.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use &lt;code&gt;IMG&lt;/code&gt; 
for &lt;a href=&quot;http://blog.neatlysliced.com/2007/07/ie6-hides-css-images/&quot;&gt;multiple overlay images in IE6&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strike&gt;Use &lt;code&gt;IMG&lt;/code&gt; with a &lt;code&gt;z-index&lt;/code&gt; in order 
to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.quackit.com/html/codes/html_stretch_background_image.cfm&quot;&gt;stretch a background image&lt;/a&gt; to fill its entire window.&lt;/strike&gt;&lt;br&gt;Note, this is no longer true with CSS3 background-size; see #6 below.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Using &lt;code&gt;img&lt;/code&gt; instead of &lt;code&gt;background-image&lt;/code&gt; can dramatically improve performance of animations over a background.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;When to use CSS background-image&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use CSS background images if the 
image &lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/questions/492809/when-to-use-img-instead-of-css-background-image/492834#492834&quot;&gt;is not part of the content&lt;/a&gt;. 
&amp;mdash;&lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/users/42147/sanchothefat&quot;&gt;sanchothefat&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use CSS background images when 
doing &lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/questions/492809/when-to-use-img-instead-of-css-background-image/492834#492834&quot;&gt;image-replacement of text&lt;/a&gt; eg. paragraphs/headers. 
&amp;mdash;&lt;a href=&quot;https://stackoverflow.com/users/42147/sanchothefat&quot;&gt;sanchothefat&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Use &lt;code&gt;background-image&lt;/code&gt; if you intend to have 
