 - &lt;code&gt;div&lt;/code&gt; is a [block element][1]
 - &lt;code&gt;span&lt;/code&gt; is an [inline element][2].

This means that to use them semantically, divs should be used to wrap sections of a document, while spans should be used to wrap small portions of text, images, etc.

&lt;h2&gt;For example:&lt;/h2&gt;

    &lt;div&gt;This a large main division, with &lt;span&gt;a small bit&lt;/span&gt; of spanned text!&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;h3&gt;Note that it is illegal to place a block-level element within an inline element, so:&lt;/h3&gt;

    &lt;div&gt;Some &lt;span&gt;text that &lt;div&gt;I want&lt;/div&gt; to mark&lt;/span&gt; up&lt;/div&gt;

...is illegal.


----------


EDIT: As of HTML5, some block elements can be placed inside of some inline elements. See the MDN reference [here][3] for a pretty clear listing. The above is still illegal, as `&lt;span&gt;` only accepts phrasing content, and `&lt;div&gt;` is flow content.


