If you are passing data to a DOM element from the server, you should set the data on the element:

    &lt;a id=&quot;foo&quot; data-foo=&quot;bar&quot; href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;foo!&lt;/a&gt;

The data can then be accessed using [`.data()`][1] in jQuery:

    console.log( $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;foo&#39;) );
    //outputs &quot;bar&quot;

However when you store data on a DOM node in jQuery *using* data, the variables are stored on the node *object*. This is to accommodate complex objects and references as storing the data on the node *element* as an attribute will only accommodate string values.

#### &lt;sub&gt;Continuing my example from above:&lt;/sub&gt;

    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;foo&#39;, &#39;baz&#39;);

    console.log( $(&#39;#foo&#39;).attr(&#39;data-foo&#39;) );
    //outputs &quot;bar&quot; as the attribute was never changed

    console.log( $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;foo&#39;) );
    //outputs &quot;baz&quot; as the value has been updated on the object

Also, the naming convention for data attributes has a bit of a hidden &quot;gotcha&quot;:

#### &lt;sub&gt;HTML:&lt;/sub&gt;

    &lt;a id=&quot;bar&quot; data-foo-bar-baz=&quot;fizz-buzz&quot; href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;fizz buzz!&lt;/a&gt;

#### &lt;sub&gt;JS:&lt;/sub&gt;

    console.log( $(&#39;#bar&#39;).data(&#39;fooBarBaz&#39;) );
    //outputs &quot;fizz-buzz&quot; as hyphens are automatically camelCase&#39;d

The hyphenated key will still work:

#### &lt;sub&gt;HTML:&lt;/sub&gt;

    &lt;a id=&quot;bar&quot; data-foo-bar-baz=&quot;fizz-buzz&quot; href=&quot;#&quot;&gt;fizz buzz!&lt;/a&gt;

#### &lt;sub&gt;JS:&lt;/sub&gt;

    console.log( $(&#39;#bar&#39;).data(&#39;foo-bar-baz&#39;) );
    //still outputs &quot;fizz-buzz&quot;

However the object returned by `.data()` will not have the hyphenated key set:

    $(&#39;#bar&#39;).data().fooBarBaz; //works
    $(&#39;#bar&#39;).data()[&#39;fooBarBaz&#39;]; //works
    $(&#39;#bar&#39;).data()[&#39;foo-bar-baz&#39;]; //does not work

It&#39;s for this reason I suggest avoiding the hyphenated key in javascript.

For HTML, keep using the hyphenated form. [HTML attributes are supposed to get ASCII-lowercased automatically][4], so `&lt;div data-foobar&gt;&lt;/div&gt;`, `&lt;DIV DATA-FOOBAR&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;`, and `&lt;dIv DaTa-FoObAr&gt;&lt;/DiV&gt;` are *supposed* to be treated as identical, but for the best compatibility the lower case form should be preferred.

The [`.data()`][1] method will also perform some basic auto-casting if the value matches a recognized pattern:

#### &lt;sub&gt;HTML:&lt;/sub&gt;

    &lt;a id=&quot;foo&quot;
        href=&quot;#&quot;
        data-str=&quot;bar&quot;
        data-bool=&quot;true&quot;
        data-num=&quot;15&quot;
        data-json=&#39;{&quot;fizz&quot;:[&quot;buzz&quot;]}&#39;&gt;foo!&lt;/a&gt;

#### &lt;sub&gt;JS:&lt;/sub&gt;

    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;str&#39;);  //`&quot;bar&quot;`
    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;bool&#39;); //`true`
    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;num&#39;);  //`15`
    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;json&#39;); //`{fizz:[&#39;buzz&#39;]}`

This auto-casting ability is very convenient for instantiating widgets &amp; plugins:

    $(&#39;.widget&#39;).each(function () {
        $(this).widget($(this).data());
        //-or-
        $(this).widget($(this).data(&#39;widget&#39;));
    });

If you absolutely must have the original value as a string, then you&#39;ll need to use [`.attr()`][2]:

#### &lt;sub&gt;HTML:&lt;/sub&gt;

    &lt;a id=&quot;foo&quot; href=&quot;#&quot; data-color=&quot;ABC123&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;a id=&quot;bar&quot; href=&quot;#&quot; data-color=&quot;654321&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;

#### &lt;sub&gt;JS:&lt;/sub&gt;

    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;color&#39;).length; //6
    $(&#39;#bar&#39;).data(&#39;color&#39;).length; //undefined, length isn&#39;t a property of numbers

    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).attr(&#39;data-color&#39;).length; //6
    $(&#39;#bar&#39;).attr(&#39;data-color&#39;).length; //6

&lt;sub&gt;This was a contrived example. For storing color values, I used to use numeric hex notation (i.e. 0xABC123), but it&#39;s worth noting that [hex was parsed incorrectly in jQuery versions before 1.7.2][3], and is no longer parsed into a `Number` as of jQuery 1.8 rc 1.&lt;/sub&gt;

**jQuery 1.8 rc 1 changed the behavior of auto-casting**. Before, any format that was a valid representation of a `Number` would be cast to `Number`. Now, values that are numeric are only auto-cast if their representation stays the same. This is best illustrated with an example.

#### &lt;sub&gt;HTML:&lt;/sub&gt;

    &lt;a id=&quot;foo&quot;
        href=&quot;#&quot;
        data-int=&quot;1000&quot;
        data-decimal=&quot;1000.00&quot;
        data-scientific=&quot;1e3&quot;
        data-hex=&quot;0x03e8&quot;&gt;foo!&lt;/a&gt;

#### &lt;sub&gt;JS:&lt;/sub&gt;

                                  // pre 1.8    post 1.8
    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;int&#39;);        //    1000        1000
    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;decimal&#39;);    //    1000   &quot;1000.00&quot;
    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;scientific&#39;); //    1000       &quot;1e3&quot;
    $(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;hex&#39;);        //    1000     &quot;0x03e8&quot;

If you plan on using alternative numeric syntaxes to access numeric values, be sure to cast the value to a `Number` first, such as with a unary `+` operator.

#### &lt;sub&gt;JS (cont.):&lt;/sub&gt;

    +$(&#39;#foo&#39;).data(&#39;hex&#39;); // 1000

[1]: http://api.jquery.com/data
[2]: http://api.jquery.com/attr
[3]: http://bugs.jquery.com/ticket/11309
[4]: http://www.w3.org/html/wg/drafts/html/master/single-page.html#attr-data-*

