The simplest and most reliable solution is inserting flex items at the right places. If they are wide enough (`width: 100%`), they will force a line break.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .container {
      background: tomato;
      display: flex;
      flex-flow: row wrap;
      align-content: space-between;
      justify-content: space-between;
    }
    .item {
      width: 100px;
      background: gold;
      height: 100px;
      border: 1px solid black;
      font-size: 30px;
      line-height: 100px;
      text-align: center;
      margin: 10px
    }
    .item:nth-child(4n - 1) {
      background: silver;
    }
    .line-break {
      width: 100%;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;1&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;2&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;3&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;line-break&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;4&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;5&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;6&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;line-break&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;7&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;8&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;9&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;line-break&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;10&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

But that&#39;s ugly and not semantic. Instead, we could generate pseudo-elements inside the flex container, and use `order` to move them to the right places.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .container {
      background: tomato;
      display: flex;
      flex-flow: row wrap;
      align-content: space-between;
      justify-content: space-between;
    }
    .item {
      width: 100px;
      background: gold;
      height: 100px;
      border: 1px solid black;
      font-size: 30px;
      line-height: 100px;
      text-align: center;
      margin: 10px
    }
    .item:nth-child(3n) {
      background: silver;
    }
    .container::before, .container::after {
      content: &#39;&#39;;
      width: 100%;
      order: 1;
    }
    .item:nth-child(n + 4) {
      order: 1;
    }
    .item:nth-child(n + 7) {
      order: 2;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;1&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;2&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;3&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;4&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;5&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;6&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;7&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;8&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;9&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

But there is a limitation: the flex container can only have a `::before` and a `::after` pseudo-element. That means you can only force 2 line breaks.

To solve that, you can generate the pseudo-elements inside the flex items instead of in the flex container. This way you won&#39;t be limited to 2. But those pseudo-elements won&#39;t be flex items, so they won&#39;t be able to force line breaks.

But luckily, [CSS Display L3][1] has introduced [`display: contents`][2] (currently only supported since [Firefox 37, Chrome 65, Safari 11.1, Edge 79][7]):

&gt; The element itself does not generate any boxes, but its children and
&gt; pseudo-elements still generate boxes as normal. For the purposes of
&gt; box generation and layout, the element must be treated as if it had
&gt; been replaced with its children and pseudo-elements in the document
&gt; tree.

So the **recommended answer to the question** is to apply `display: contents` to the children of the flex container, and wrap the contents of each one inside an additional wrapper. Then, the flex items will be those additional wrappers and the pseudo-elements of the children.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .container {
      background: tomato;
      display: flex;
      flex-wrap: wrap;
      align-content: space-between;
      justify-content: space-between;
    }
    .item {
      display: contents;
    }
    .item &gt; div {
      width: 100px;
      background: gold;
      height: 100px;
      border: 1px solid black;
      font-size: 30px;
      line-height: 100px;
      text-align: center;
      margin: 10px;
    }
    .item:nth-child(3n) &gt; div {
      background: silver;
    }
    .item:nth-child(3n)::after {
      content: &#39;&#39;;
      width: 100%;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;1&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;2&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;3&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;4&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;5&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;6&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;7&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;8&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;9&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;10&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Alternatively, according to [an old version of the spec][3], Flexbox allowed forced breaks by using [`break-before`][4], [`break-after`][5] or their old CSS 2.1 aliases:

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .item:nth-child(3n) {
      page-break-after: always; /* CSS 2.1 syntax */
      break-after: always; /* CSS 3 syntax */
    }

But these forced line breaks only work on Firefox, and I don&#39;t think they are supposed to work according to the current spec. The new proposed way (not implemented anywhere) is with [`wrap-before` or `wrap-after`][6]:

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .item:nth-child(3n) {
      wrap-after: flex; /* New proposed syntax */
    }

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .container {
      background: tomato;
      display: flex;
      flex-flow: row wrap;
      align-content: space-between;
      justify-content: space-between;
    }
    .item {
      width: 100px;
      background: gold;
      height: 100px;
      border: 1px solid black;
      font-size: 30px;
      line-height: 100px;
      text-align: center;
      margin: 10px
    }
    .item:nth-child(3n) {
      page-break-after: always;
      break-after: always;
      wrap-after: flex;
      background: silver;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;1&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;2&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;3&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;4&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;5&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;6&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;7&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;8&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;9&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;item&quot;&gt;10&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


