# `page-break-after` is now [deprecated][1]. Use [`break-after: page`][2] instead.

```css
@media print {
    .page, .page-break { break-after: page; }
}
```

You can use it like:

```html
&lt;div class=&quot;page&quot;&gt;This is on a separate page...&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;page&quot;&gt;...then this.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Or you could use a breaker div...&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;page-break&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div&gt;...like so&lt;/div&gt;
```

# Original Answer

Add a CSS class called &quot;pagebreak&quot; (or &quot;pb&quot;), like so:

```css
@media print {
    .pagebreak { page-break-before: always; } /* page-break-after works, as well */
}
```

    

Then add an empty DIV tag ([or any block element that generates a box][1]) where you want the page break.

```html
&lt;div class=&quot;pagebreak&quot;&gt; &lt;/div&gt;
```

It won&#39;t show up on the page, but will break up the page when printing.


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/page-break-after
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/break-after

P.S. Perhaps this only applies when using `-after` (and also what else you might be doing with other `&lt;div&gt;`s on the page), but I found that I had to augment the CSS class as follows:

```css
@media print {
    .pagebreak {
        clear: both;
        page-break-after: always;
    }
}
```

