Use either [`auto-fill`][1] or [`auto-fit`][2] as the first argument of the [`repeat()`][3] notation.

[`&lt;auto-repeat&gt;`][4] variant of the `repeat()` notation:

    repeat( [ auto-fill | auto-fit ] , [ &lt;line-names&gt;? &lt;fixed-size&gt; ]+ &lt;line-names&gt;? )

___
`auto-fill`
-----------------

&gt; When `auto-fill` is given as the repetition number, if the grid
&gt; container has a [definite][5] size or max size in the relevant axis, then
&gt; the number of repetitions is the largest possible positive integer
&gt; that does not cause the grid to overflow its grid container.
&gt;
&gt; &lt;sup&gt;*https://www.w3.org/TR/css-grid-1/#valdef-repeat-auto-fill*&lt;/sup&gt;

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-gap: 10px;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, 186px);
    }

    .grid&gt;* {
      background-color: green;
      height: 200px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;grid&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;1&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;2&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;3&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;4&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The grid will repeat as many tracks as possible without overflowing its container. 

[![Using auto-fill as the repetition number of the repeat() notation][6]][6]

In this case, given the example above *(see image)*, only 5 tracks can fit the grid-container without overflowing. There are only 4 items in our grid, so a fifth one is created as an empty track within the remaining space.

The rest of the remaining space, track #6, ends the explicit grid. This means there was not enough space to place another track.

___

`auto-fit`
----------

&gt; The `auto-fit` keyword behaves the same as `auto-fill`, except
&gt; that after [grid item placement][7] any empty repeated tracks are collapsed.
&gt;
&gt; &lt;sup&gt;*https://www.w3.org/TR/css-grid-1/#valdef-repeat-auto-fit*&lt;/sup&gt;


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-gap: 10px;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, 186px);
    }

    .grid&gt;* {
      background-color: green;
      height: 200px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;grid&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;1&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;2&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;3&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;4&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The grid will still repeat as many tracks as possible without overflowing its container, but the empty tracks will be collapsed to `0`.

A collapsed track is treated as having a fixed track sizing function of `0px`.

[![Using auto-fit as the repetition number of the repeat() notation][8]][8]

Unlike the `auto-fill` image example, the empty fifth track is collapsed, ending the explicit grid right after the 4th item.

___

`auto-fill` vs `auto-fit`
-------------------------

The difference between the two is noticeable when the [`minmax()`][9] function is used.

Use `minmax(186px, 1fr)` to range the items from `186px` to a [fraction of the leftover space in the grid container][10].

When using `auto-fill`, the items will grow once there is no space to place empty tracks.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-gap: 10px;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(186px, 1fr));
    }

    .grid&gt;* {
      background-color: green;
      height: 200px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;grid&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;1&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;2&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;3&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;4&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

When using `auto-fit`, the items will grow to fill the remaining space because all the empty tracks will be collapsed to `0px`.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-gap: 10px;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(186px, 1fr));
    }

    .grid&gt;* {
      background-color: green;
      height: 200px;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;grid&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;1&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;2&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;3&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;4&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;
