You can create files in browser using [`Blob`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Blob) and [`URL.createObjectURL`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/URL.createObjectURL). All recent browsers [support this](http://caniuse.com/#search=blob%20urls).

You can not directly save the file you create, since that would cause massive security problems, but you can provide it as a download link for the user. You can suggest a file name via the [`download` attribute](http://davidwalsh.name/download-attribute) of the link, in browsers that support the download attribute. As with any other download, the user downloading the file will have the final say on the file name though.

    var textFile = null,
      makeTextFile = function (text) {
        var data = new Blob([text], {type: &#39;text/plain&#39;});
    
        // If we are replacing a previously generated file we need to
        // manually revoke the object URL to avoid memory leaks.
        if (textFile !== null) {
          window.URL.revokeObjectURL(textFile);
        }
    
        textFile = window.URL.createObjectURL(data);

        // returns a URL you can use as a href
        return textFile;
      };

Here&#39;s an [example](http://jsfiddle.net/UselessCode/qm5AG/) that uses this technique to save arbitrary text from a `textarea`.

If you want to immediately initiate the download instead of requiring the user to click on a link, you can use mouse events to simulate a mouse click on the link as [Lifecube](https://stackoverflow.com/users/661035/lifecube)&#39;s [answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/21012821/778975) did. I&#39;ve created an [updated example](http://jsfiddle.net/k56eezxp/) that uses this technique.

      var create = document.getElementById(&#39;create&#39;),
        textbox = document.getElementById(&#39;textbox&#39;);
    
      create.addEventListener(&#39;click&#39;, function () {
        var link = document.createElement(&#39;a&#39;);
        link.setAttribute(&#39;download&#39;, &#39;info.txt&#39;);
        link.href = makeTextFile(textbox.value);
        document.body.appendChild(link);
    
        // wait for the link to be added to the document
        window.requestAnimationFrame(function () {
          var event = new MouseEvent(&#39;click&#39;);
          link.dispatchEvent(event);
          document.body.removeChild(link);
    	});
        
      }, false);

