**How it works**

 1. [Establish a block-level grid container.](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#grid-containers) (`inline-grid` would be the other option)
 2. The [**`grid-auto-rows`**](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#auto-tracks) property sets the height of automatically generated rows. In this grid each row is 50px tall.
 3. The [**`grid-gap`**](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#gutters) property is a shorthand for `grid-column-gap` and `grid-row-gap`. This rule sets a 10px gap *between* grid items. (It doesn&#39;t apply to the area between items and the container.)
 4. The [**`grid-template-columns`**](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#track-sizing) property sets the width of explicitly defined columns.

    The [**`repeat`**](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#repeat-notation) notation defines a pattern of repeating columns (or rows).

    The [**`auto-fill`**](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#auto-repeat) function tells the grid to line up as many columns (or rows) as possible without overflowing the container. (This can create a similar behavior to flex layout&#39;s `flex-wrap: wrap`.)

    The [**`minmax()`**](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#valdef-grid-template-columns-minmax) function sets a minimum and maximum size range for each column (or row). In the code above, the width of each column will be a minimum of 30% of the container and maximum of whatever free space is available.

    The [**`fr`** unit](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#fr-unit) represents a fraction of the free space in the grid container. It&#39;s comparable to flexbox&#39;s `flex-grow` property.

 5. With [**`grid-row`**](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#placement-shorthands) and [**`span`**](https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-grid-layout/#common-uses-numeric) we&#39;re telling grid items how many rows they should span across.


