First of all note that `vertical-align` is only applicable to table cells and inline-level elements.

There are couple of ways to achieve vertical alignments which may or may not meet your needs. However I&#39;ll show you [two][1] [methods][2] from my favorites:

# 1. Using `transform` and `top`

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .valign {
        position: relative;
        top: 50%;
        transform: translateY(-50%);
        /* vendor prefixes omitted due to brevity */
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div style=&quot;position: absolute; left: 50px; top: 50px;&quot;&gt;
        &lt;div style=&quot;text-align: left; position: absolute;height: 56px;background-color: pink;&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;valign&quot; style=&quot;background-color: lightblue;&quot;&gt;test&lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The key point is that a percentage value on `top` is relative to the `height` of the containing block; While a percentage value on `transform`s is relative to the size of the box itself (the bounding box).

If you experience [font rendering issues][5] (blurry font), the fix is to add `perspective(1px)` to the `transform` declaration so it becomes:

    transform: perspective(1px) translateY(-50%);

It&#39;s worth noting that CSS `transform` [is supported in IE9+][3].

# 2. Using `inline-block` (pseudo-)elements

In this method, we have two sibling `inline-block` elements which are aligned vertically at the middle by `vertical-align: middle` declaration.

One of them has a `height` of `100%` of its parent and the other is our desired element whose we wanted to align it at the middle.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .parent {
        text-align: left;
        position: absolute;
        height: 56px;
        background-color: pink;
        white-space: nowrap;
        font-size: 0; /* remove the gap between inline level elements */
    }

    .dummy-child { height: 100%; }

    .valign {
        font-size: 16px; /* re-set the font-size */
    }

    .dummy-child, .valign {
        display: inline-block;
        vertical-align: middle;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div style=&quot;position: absolute; left: 50px; top: 50px;&quot;&gt;
        &lt;div class=&quot;parent&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;dummy-child&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;valign&quot; style=&quot;background-color: lightblue;&quot;&gt;test&lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Finally, we should use one of the [available methods to remove the gap between inline-level elements][4].


