Adding to vectran&#39;s answer: You also have to set `cellspacing` attribute on the table element for cross-browser compatibility.

    &lt;table cellspacing=&quot;0&quot;&gt;

EDIT (for the sake of completeness I&#39;m expanding this 5 years later:):



**Internet Explorer 6** and **Internet Explorer 7** required you to set [cellspacing][1] directly as a table attribute, otherwise the spacing wouldn&#39;t vanish.

**Internet Explorer 8** and later versions and all other versions of popular browsers - **Chrome, Firefox, Opera 4+** - support the CSS property [border-spacing][2].

So in order to make a cross-browser table cell spacing reset (supporting IE6 as a dinosaur browser), you can follow the below code sample:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    table{
      border: 1px solid black;
    }
    table td {
      border: 1px solid black; /* Style just to show the table cell boundaries */
    }


    table.no-spacing {
      border-spacing:0; /* Removes the cell spacing via CSS */
      border-collapse: collapse;  /* Optional - if you don&#39;t want to have double border where cells touch */
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;Default table:&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;table&gt;
      &lt;tr&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;First cell&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;Second cell&lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/table&gt;

    &lt;p&gt;Removed spacing:&lt;/p&gt;

    &lt;table class=&quot;no-spacing&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot;&gt; &lt;!-- cellspacing 0 to support IE6 and IE7 --&gt;
      &lt;tr&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;First cell&lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;Second cell&lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/table&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/HTMLTableElement.cellSpacing
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/border-spacing

