As @warfield pointed out in his [answer][1]  from next.js &gt;= 12.1 relative URLs are no longer allowed in redirects and using them will throw an error. I&#39;m reposting here his answer for more visibility : 

&gt; To redirect using [middleware][2] with Next.js &gt;= 12.1:
&gt; 1. Create a `middleware.ts` (or .js) file at the same level as your `pages` directory
&gt; 2. Export a `middleware` function
&gt; 3. Create an [absolute URL][3] and pass it to `redirect`
&gt; 
&gt; TypeScript example `middleware.ts`:
&gt; 
&gt; ```
&gt; 
&gt; import { NextResponse } from &#39;next/server&#39;
&gt; import type { NextRequest } from &#39;next/server&#39;
&gt; 
&gt; export function middleware(request: NextRequest) {   
&gt;   const url = request.nextUrl.clone()   
&gt;   if (url.pathname === &#39;/&#39;) {
&gt;     url.pathname = &#39;/hello-nextjs&#39;
&gt;     return NextResponse.redirect(url)   
&gt;   } 
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; ```



[1]: https://nextjs.org/docs/messages/middleware-relative-urls#possible-ways-to-fix-it
  [2]: https://nextjs.org/docs/advanced-features/middleware
