You don&#39;t want to stretch the span in height?  
You have the possiblity to affect one or more flex-items to don&#39;t stretch the full height of the container.

***To affect all flex-items of the container, choose this:***  
You have to set `align-items: flex-start;` to `div` and all flex-items of this container get the height of their content.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    div {
      align-items: flex-start;
      background: tan;
      display: flex;
      height: 200px;
    }
    span {
      background: red;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;This is some text.&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

***To affect only a single flex-item, choose this:***  
If you want to unstretch a single flex-item on the container, you have to set `align-self: flex-start;` to this flex-item. All other flex-items of the container aren&#39;t affected.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    div {
      display: flex;
      height: 200px;
      background: tan;
    }
    span.only {
      background: red;
      align-self:flex-start;
    }
    span {
        background:green;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;span class=&quot;only&quot;&gt;This is some text.&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;This is more text.&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

**Why is this happening to the `span`?**  
The default value of the property `align-items` is `stretch`. This is the reason why the `span` fill the height of the `div`.

**Difference between `baseline` and `flex-start`?**  
If you have some text on the flex-items, with different font-sizes, you can use the baseline of the first line to place the flex-item vertically. A flex-item with a smaller font-size have some space between the container and itself at top. With `flex-start` the flex-item will be set to the top of the container (without space).

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    div {
      align-items: baseline;
      background: tan;
      display: flex;
      height: 200px;
    }
    span {
      background: red;
    }
    span.fontsize {
      font-size:2em;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div&gt;
      &lt;span class=&quot;fontsize&quot;&gt;This is some text.&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;This is more text.&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

&gt; You can find more information about the difference between `baseline` and `flex-start` here:  
**https://stackoverflow.com/q/34606879/3597276**

