## New solution (2022)

CSS has changed since this aswer was written. We now have several properties that can drasticaly simplify code for a square grid : 

 - The **grid** property to handle the grid layout ([MDN reference][1])
 - The **aspect ratio** property to handle the square aspect ratio of each grid item ([MDN reference][2])
 - The **object-fit** property to handle image centering and wether they should cover the square or not ([MDN reference][3])

Here is an example : 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
      gap: 2%;
    }

    .square {
      aspect-ratio: 1/ 1;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      padding: 5%;
      background-color: #1E1E1E;
      color: #fff;
    }

    .square img {
      width: 100%;
      height: 100%;
      object-fit: contain;
      object-position: center;
    }

    .square.fullImg {
      padding: 0;
    }

    .square.fullImg img {
      object-fit: cover;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;grid&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
        &lt;ul&gt;This demo shows you can center multiple types of content :
          &lt;li&gt;Text&lt;/li&gt;
          &lt;li&gt;Images&lt;/li&gt;
          &lt;li&gt;Lists&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;/ul&gt;
