# `LinkButton` component - a solution for React Router v4

First, a note about many other answers to this question.

## ⚠️ Nesting `&lt;button&gt;` and `&lt;a&gt;` is not valid html. ⚠️

Any answer here which suggests nesting a html `button` in a React Router `Link` component (or vice-versa) will render in a web browser, but it is not semantic, accessible, or valid html:

    &lt;a stuff-here&gt;&lt;button&gt;label text&lt;/button&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;button&gt;&lt;a stuff-here&gt;label text&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/button&gt;

☝[Click to validate this markup with validator.w3.org](https://validator.w3.org/nu/?showsource=yes&amp;doc=http%3A%2F%2Fdropbox.beausmith.com%2Fstatic-html%2Finvalid-button-anchor-markup.html) ☝

This can lead to layout/styling issues as buttons are not typically placed inside links.

---

## Using an html `&lt;button&gt;` tag with React Router `&lt;Link&gt;` component.

If you only want  an html `button` tag…

    &lt;button&gt;label text&lt;/button&gt;

…then, here&#39;s the right way to get a button that works like React Router’s `Link` component…

Use React Router’s [withRouter](https://reacttraining.com/react-router/web/api/withRouter) HOC to pass these props to your component:

- `history`
- `location`
- `match`
- `staticContext`

---

# `LinkButton` component

Here’s a `LinkButton` component for you to copy/*pasta*:

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    // file: /components/LinkButton.jsx
    import React from &#39;react&#39;
    import PropTypes from &#39;prop-types&#39;
    import { withRouter } from &#39;react-router&#39;

    const LinkButton = (props) =&gt; {
      const {
        history,
        location,
        match,
        staticContext,
        to,
        onClick,
        // ⬆ filtering out props that `button` doesn’t know what to do with.
        ...rest
      } = props
      return (
        &lt;button
          {...rest} // `children` is just another prop!
          onClick={(event) =&gt; {
            onClick &amp;&amp; onClick(event)
            history.push(to)
          }}
        /&gt;
      )
    }

    LinkButton.propTypes = {
      to: PropTypes.string.isRequired,
      children: PropTypes.node.isRequired
    }

    export default withRouter(LinkButton)

Then import the component:

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    import LinkButton from &#39;/components/LinkButton&#39;

Use the component:

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    &lt;LinkButton to=&#39;/path/to/page&#39;&gt;Push My Buttons!&lt;/LinkButton&gt;

If you need an onClick method:

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    &lt;LinkButton
      to=&#39;/path/to/page&#39;
      onClick={(event) =&gt; {
        console.log(&#39;custom event here!&#39;, event)
      }}
    &gt;Push My Buttons!&lt;/LinkButton&gt;

**Update:** If you&#39;re looking for another fun option made available after the above was written, check out this [useRouter hook](https://usehooks.com/useRouter/).

