[Koen&#39;s answer][koen] doesn&#39;t exactly center the element.

The proper way is to use CSS3 `transform` property, although it&#39;s [not supported in some old browsers][1]. We don&#39;t even need to set a fixed or relative `width`.

```css
.centered {
    position: fixed;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translate(-50%, 0);
}
```

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .almost-centered {
        background-color: #eee;
        position: fixed;
        width: 40%;
        text-align: center;
        top: 5%;
        left: 50%;
        padding: 20px;
        margin-left: -20%;
    }

    .centered {
        background-color: #eee;
        position: fixed;
        width: 40%;
        text-align: center;
        top: 25%;
        left: 50%;
        padding: 20px;
        transform: translate(-50%, 0);
    }

