When W3C was working on HTML5, they discovered all browsers have &quot;text/javascript&quot; as the default script `type`, so [they standardized it to be the default value][1]. Hence, you don&#39;t need `type` either.

For pages in XHTML 1.0 or HTML 4.01 omitting `type` is considered invalid. Try [validating][2] the following:

    &lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;
    &lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot; xml:lang=&quot;en&quot; lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;
    &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;script src=&quot;http://example.com/test.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
    &lt;/head&gt;
    &lt;body/&gt;
    &lt;/html&gt;

You will be informed of the following error:

&gt; Line 4, Column 41: required attribute &quot;type&quot; not specified

So if you&#39;re a fan of standards, use it. It should have no practical effect, but, when in doubt, may as well go by the spec.


  [1]: http://www.w3.org/TR/html5/scripting-1.html#attr-script-type
  [2]: http://validator.w3.org/

