Although the below is still worth reading for the useful info, we have had Flexbox for some time now, so just use that, as per [this answer][1].


----------


**You can&#39;t use:**

`vertical-align:middle` because [it&#39;s ***not*** applicable to block-level elements][2]

 `margin-top:auto` and `margin-bottom:auto` because [their used values would compute as ***zero***][3]

`margin-top:-50%` because [percentage-based margin values are calculated relative to the ***width*** of containing block ][4]


In fact, the nature of document flow and [element height calculation algorithms][3] make it impossible to use margins for centering an element vertically inside its parent. Whenever a vertical margin&#39;s value is changed, it will trigger a parent element height re-calculation (re-flow), which would in turn trigger a re-center of the original element... making it an infinite loop.

**You can use:**

[A few workarounds like this][5] which work for your scenario; the three elements have to be nested like so:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .container {
        display: table;
        height: 100%;
        position: absolute;
        overflow: hidden;
        width: 100%;
    }
    .helper {
        #position: absolute;
        #top: 50%;
        display: table-cell;
        vertical-align: middle;
    }
    .content {
        #position: relative;
        #top: -50%;
        margin: 0 auto;
        width: 200px;
        border: 1px solid orange;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;
        &lt;div class=&quot;helper&quot;&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;content&quot;&gt;
                &lt;p&gt;stuff&lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


[JSFiddle][6] works fine according to Browsershot.


